<page_title>Pressure-induced structural transformations between polymorphs</page_title>
<text>Pressure can cause one polymorph to change into another within a crystal
p. 4 of 7

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;



 
  

Which polymorph is softer?

The result that polymorph-II can be compressed into polymorph-I without heating means that polymorph-II is softer, even though it has a higher melting point. The mechanical stability (characterized by hardness) and the thermal stability (characterized by melting point) don&apos;t necessarily go together. In other words, a harder crystal does not necessarily have a higher melting point, and a softer crystal does not necessarily have a lower melting point.

Here is a hands-on setup that allows you to compress this system with your fingers, using a steering force on the piston.

Not all molecular crystals can be compressed into another polymorph. The next model shows a different result.

